ublic sphere. Without excluding the phenomenon of terrorists, it maps the whole field of Muslim visibility. The nine contributions present unpublished ethnographic materials that have been collected between 2003 and 2005. They track down the available space that is open to Muslims in EU member states claiming a visibility of their own. The volume collects male and female, secular and religious, radical and pietistic voices of sometimes very young people. They all speak about »being a Muslim in Europe« and the meaning of »real Islam«.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aIslam and politics. 0aMuslims. 4aEurope. 4aIslam. 4aIslamic Studies. 4aPolitics. 4aPublic Space. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aEurope.  aIslam.  aIslamic Studies.  aPolitics.  aPublic Space.1 aAbdel-Samad, Hamed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmiraux, Valérie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmiraux, Valérie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoender, Welmoet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFadil, Nadia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrisina, Annalisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJonker, Gerdien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJonker, Gerdien, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLewis, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYurdakul, Gökce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of e